'''Delaware Route 404''' ('''DE 404''') is a major [[state highway]] in [[Sussex County, Delaware|Sussex County]], [[Delaware]] that spans the width of the state.  DE 404's western terminus is at the [[Maryland]] border northwest of [[Bridgeville, Delaware|Bridgeville]], where it continues as [[Maryland Route 404]] (MD 404), and its eastern terminus is at the [[Five Points, Delaware|Five Points]] intersection with [[U.S. Route 9 in Delaware|U.S. Route 9]] (US 9), [[Delaware Route 1|DE 1]], and [[U.S. Route 9 Business (Lewes, Delaware)|US 9 Business]] (US 9 Bus.). The route passes through rural areas as well as the towns of Bridgeville and [[Georgetown, Delaware|Georgetown]]. DE 404 runs [[concurrency (road)|concurrent]] with [[Delaware Route 18|DE 18]] from east of Bridgeville to Georgetown and with US 9 from Georgetown to Five Points. DE 404 has a business route, [[Delaware Route 404 Business|DE 404 Bus.]], that passes through Bridgeville. DE 404, along with MD 404, serves as a major route connecting the [[Chesapeake Bay Bridge]] and the [[Baltimore-Washington Metropolitan Area]] with the [[Delaware beaches]]. 

DE 404 was first designated by 1936 to run from the Maryland border to DE 18 southeast of Bridgeville. The route was extended to Five Points by 1987.  By 1999, DE 404 was aligned to bypass Bridgeville, with DE 404 Bus. designated on the former route through the town. The new alignment of DE 404 around Bridgeville replaced [[Delaware Route 404 Alternate|DE 404 Alternate]] (DE 404 Alt.)

==Route description==
[[File:DE 18-DE 404 WB shields past The Circle.jpg|thumb|right|DE 18/DE 404 westbound past US 9 at The Circle in Georgetown]]
DE 404 begins at the [[Maryland]] border, where it continues northwest into that state as [[Maryland Route 404|MD 404]]. From the state line, the route heads southeast on two-lane undivided Seashore Highway, passing through a mix of farmland and woodland with some homes. In the community of [[Scotts Corner, Delaware|Scotts Corner]], the road intersects the western terminus of [[Delaware Route 36|DE 36]]. DE 404 continues through more rural areas and turns northeast onto Newton Road, with [[Delaware Route 404 Business|DE 404 Bus.]] continuing southeast along Seashore Highway toward [[Bridgeville, Delaware|Bridgeville]]. From here, DE 404 heads through agricultural areas to the north of Bridgeville, curving east and crossing [[Norfolk Southern]]'s Delmarva Secondary railroad line. The route comes to an intersection with [[U.S. Route 13 in Delaware|US 13]] and turns south to form a [[concurrency (road)|concurrency]] with that route on Sussex Highway, a four-lane [[divided highway]]. A short distance later, [[U.S. Route 13 Business (Bridgeville, Delaware)|US 13 Bus.]] splits off to the southwest to head into Bridgeville. The road continues through farmland with some businesses to the east of Bridgeville. Upon reaching an intersection with US 13 Bus./DE 404 Bus., DE 404 splits from US 13 by heading southeast onto four-lane divided Seashore Highway. The road passes a few businesses before becoming two lanes and undivided as it continues through agricultural areas, coming to an intersection with [[Delaware Route 18|DE 18]].<ref name="DE 2008 map">{{Delaware road map|year=2008}}</ref><ref name="google">{{google maps |url=http://maps.google.com/maps?saddr=delaware+404+and+maryland+404&daddr=38.76259,-75.60926+to:38.7061129,-75.5153511+to:delaware+1+and+delaware+404&hl=en&sll=38.778585,-75.447105&sspn=0.259614,0.676346&geocode=FYgRUAId55h8-ynBCPD3JWC4iTGtY93nuvPhdQ%3BFV54TwIdVEt--ykdgKIProy4iTHGG3Aidogg9Q%3BFcCbTgIdKbp_-yk_ASwveO24iTFQAuAte7Oumw%3BFeZATwIdlfCE-ylvQyNmybm4iTF2HvutM7z3pw&vpsrc=0&mra=dpe&mrsp=1&sz=11&via=1,2&t=h&z=11|title=overview of Delaware Route 404|accessdate=November 16, 2011}}</ref>

At this point, DE 18 heads east concurrent with DE 404 along Seashore Highway, running through a mix of farmland and woodland with some residences. The road heads through more forested areas with some agriculture and homes, passing through tracts of the [[Redden State Forest]]. Farther east, DE 18/DE 404 heads into [[Georgetown, Delaware|Georgetown]], passing to the north of [[Delaware Technical Community College]]'s Jack F. Owens Campus. The road crosses [[U.S. Route 113|US 113]] in a commercial area and continues east. The two routes head southeast onto North Bedford Street, passing homes and businesses. The road comes to an intersection with [[U.S. Route 9 in Delaware|US 9]] at The Circle in the center of Georgetown, where DE 18 ends.<ref name="DE 2008 map"/><ref name="google"/>

[[File:DE 1 SB at Five Points.JPG|thumb|200px|left|Erroneous US 404 shield along [[Delaware Route 1|DE 1]] in [[Five Points, Delaware|Five Points]]]]At this point, DE 404 continues northeast concurrent with US 9 on East Market Street, lined with downtown businesses. The road crosses Norfolk Southern's Indian River Secondary railroad line and runs through residential areas with a few commercial establishments. US 9/DE 404 heads east-northeast out of Georgetown and becomes Lewes Georgetown Highway, passing through farmland with some homes and businesses. The two routes intersect the eastern terminus of [[U.S. Route 9 Truck (Georgetown, Delaware)|US 9 Truck]] and run through wooded areas with some fields and development. In [[Gravel Hill, Delaware|Gravel Hill]], the road intersects [[Delaware Route 30|DE 30]]. Following this intersection, US 9/DE 404 passes through more farmland and woodland with some residences, reaching a junction with [[Delaware Route 5|DE 5]] in [[Harbeson, Delaware|Harbeson]]. The two routes run through more rural areas, crossing a [[Delaware Coast Line Railroad]] line. The road heads through farmland with increasing residential subdivisions. Upon reaching the area of the [[Five Points, Delaware|Five Points]] intersection in [[Nassau, Delaware|Nassau]], US 9/DE 404 runs past homes and businesses, widening into a divided highway and coming to an intersection with [[Delaware Route 1D|DE 1D]]/[[Delaware Route 23|DE 23]]. These two routes join US 9/DE 404 for a concurrency on a four-lane divided highway before the road comes to a junction with [[Delaware Route 1|DE 1]]. Here, DE 1D/DE 23/DE 404 all end, [[U.S. Route 9 Business (Lewes, Delaware)|US 9 Bus.]] continues northeast, and US 9 heads east for a concurrency with DE 1.<ref name="DE 2008 map"/><ref name="google"/>

DE 404 serves as a major route connecting the [[Chesapeake Bay Bridge]] and the [[Baltimore-Washington Metropolitan Area]] to the [[Delaware beaches]].<ref name=wjla>{{cite web|url=http://www.wjla.com/blogs/weather/2011/06/delmarva-beach-forecast-for-the-4th-of-july-weekend-11637.html|title=Delmarva beach forecast for the 4th of July weekend|date=July 1, 2011|publisher=[[WJLA-TV]]|accessdate=November 16, 2011}}</ref><ref name=wp>{{cite news|last=Sottili|first=Carol|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/05/20/AR2010052003730.html|title=How to beat the beach traffic|date=May 20, 2012|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 14, 2012}}</ref> The highest [[annual average daily traffic]] along DE 404 is 30,773 vehicles along the US 13 concurrency with the lowest being 5,777 vehicles at the western terminus of DE 404 Business.<ref name=DelDOT>{{cite web |author= Staff |title= Traffic Count and Mileage Report: Interstate, Delaware, and US Routes |publisher= [[Delaware Department of Transportation]] |year= 2011 |url= http://www.deldot.gov/information/pubs_forms/manuals/traffic_counts/2011/pdf/2011_Interstate_DE_US.pdf |format= PDF |accessdate= May&nbsp;17, 2012}}</ref> All of DE 404 is part of the [[National Highway System (United States)|National Highway System]] with the exception of the portion along Newton Road in Bridgeville.<ref name="NHS">{{cite map|publisher=[[Federal Highway Administration]]|title=National Highway System: Delaware|url=http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/planning/nhs/maps/de/de_delaware.pdf|year=2010|format=PDF|accessdate=February&nbsp;10, 2012}}</ref>

==History==
By 1920, what would originally become DE 404 was an unimproved county road, with the section east of Bridgeville under contract as a state highway.<ref name="DE 1920 map">{{Delaware road map|year=1920}}</ref> The entire route of what would become DE 404 was completed as a state highway to a point northwest of Bridgeville by 1924.<ref name="DE 1924 map">{{Delaware road map|year=1924}}</ref> By 1931, the road was built as a state highway northwest to the Maryland border.<ref name="DE 1931 map">{{Delaware road map|year=1931}}</ref> When Delaware designated its state highways by 1936, DE 404 was designated to run from the Maryland border, where it connected to MD 404, southeast to DE 18 southeast of Bridgeville. The route followed its current alignment to Bridgeville, where it passed through the town on Market Street and South Main Street before picking up its current alignment east of US 13. At this time, what is now DE 404 past its then-eastern terminus was designated as part of DE 18.<ref name="DE 1936 map">{{Delaware road map|year=1936}}</ref> By 1987, DE 404 was extended east to DE 1 in Five Points, following DE 18 to Georgetown and US 9 (which had replaced a portion of DE 18) from Georgetown to Five Points.<ref name="DE 1987 map">{{Delaware road map|year=1987}}</ref> By 1990, DE 404 Alternate was created to bypass Bridgeville to the north and east, following Newton Road and US 13.<ref name="DE 1990 map">{{Delaware road map|year=1990}}</ref> DE 404 Alternate became a part of DE 404 by 1999, with the former DE 404 through Bridgeville becoming DE 404 Business.<ref name="DE 1999 map">{{Delaware road map|year=1999}}</ref>

